# Arch Linux Installation from Scratch

## What it is
Manual Arch Linux installation with no installer,
no GUI assistance. Every decision made manually
through terminal.

## My Setup
- Disk: SSD solo boot, no dual boot
- Partition table: GPT using gdisk
- Filesystem: ext4
- Bootloader: GRUB
- Desktop: KDE Plasma
- AUR helper: yay

## Partition Layout

| Partition | Size | Purpose |
|-----------|------|---------|
| /boot/efi | 512mb | EFI system partition |
| swap | 8gb | Overflow and hibernation |
| / | Remaining disk | Root filesystem |

## Why GPT over MBR
gdisk creates GPT partition tables.
GPT is the modern standard — supports disks
over 2TB, supports UEFI, more reliable than
legacy MBR. No reason to use MBR on modern hardware.

## Why swap equals RAM
8gb RAM means 8gb swap.
This ratio allows full hibernation —
entire RAM contents written to swap on shutdown
and restored on boot. System resumes exactly
where you left it.

## Installation Steps

### 1. Boot into Arch ISO
```bash
# verify boot mode is UEFI
ls /sys/firmware/efi/efivars
# if directory exists you are in UEFI mode
```

### 2. Connect to internet
```bash
iwctl
device list
station wlan0 scan
station wlan0 get-networks
station wlan0 connect YOURNETWORK
exit

# verify connection
ping archlinux.org
```

### 3. Partition the disk
```bash
# identify your disk
lsblk

# open gdisk
gdisk /dev/sda

# inside gdisk:
# n → new partition
# partition 1 → +512M → type EF00 (EFI)
# partition 2 → +8G   → type 8200 (swap)
# partition 3 → rest  → type 8300 (Linux)
# w → write and exit
```

### 4. Format partitions
```bash
# format EFI partition
mkfs.fat -F32 /dev/sda1

# format swap
mkswap /dev/sda2
swapon /dev/sda2

# format root
mkfs.ext4 /dev/sda3
```

### 5. Mount partitions
```bash
mount /dev/sda3 /mnt
mkdir -p /mnt/boot/efi
mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot/efi
```

### 6. Install base system
```bash
pacstrap /mnt base base-devel linux linux-firmware
```

### 7. Generate fstab
```bash
genfstab -U /mnt >> /mnt/etc/fstab
# -U uses UUIDs not device names
# safer across reboots
```

### 8. Enter the system
```bash
arch-chroot /mnt
```

### 9. System configuration
```bash
# timezone
ln -sf /usr/share/zoneinfo/Asia/Kolkata /etc/localtime
hwclock --systohc

# locale
echo "en_US.UTF-8 UTF-8" >> /etc/locale.gen
locale-gen
echo "LANG=en_US.UTF-8" > /etc/locale.conf

# hostname
echo "archbox" > /etc/hostname

# root password
passwd
```

### 10. Install GRUB
```bash
pacman -S grub efibootmgr
grub-install --target=x86_64-efi \
             --efi-directory=/boot/efi \
             --bootloader-id=GRUB
grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg
```

### 11. Install KDE Plasma
```bash
pacman -S plasma kde-applications
pacman -S sddm
systemctl enable sddm
systemctl enable NetworkManager
```

### 12. Create user
```bash
useradd -m -G wheel username
passwd username

# enable sudo for wheel group
EDITOR=nano visudo
# uncomment %wheel ALL=(ALL) ALL
```

### 13. Install yay AUR helper
```bash
# as your user not root
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/yay.git
cd yay
makepkg -si
```

### 14. Reboot
```bash
exit
umount -R /mnt
reboot
```

## What I Learned

- GPT is not just a partition table, it is
  a complete rethinking of how disks are addressed
- fstab using UUIDs means partitions mount correctly
  even if disk order changes on boot
- arch-chroot changes root context completely,
  you are operating inside the new system
  before it even boots
- GRUB needs to know EFI directory at install time
  not just at boot time
- swap sized to RAM is not optional if you
  want hibernation to actually work

## Why This Matters
Anyone can install Ubuntu.
Manual Arch installation means you understand
what an operating system actually needs to exist.
Bootloader, filesystem, base packages, locale,
users — nothing is hidden, nothing is automatic.
